        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected width of the water vapor absorption feature is about 1 km/sec.  The requested spectral window provides a resolution which may provides reasonable sampling.

A second spectral window also cenetered on the expected line of 937 MHz width is requested.  This will provide sufficient sensitivity for self calibration in the middle of the 325 GHz water line on Ceres given Ceres' 1.3 Jy flux density.

The remaining two spectral windows are to provide improved calibration and self calibration on Ceres.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>At the expected time of the observations Ceres will have an apparent diameter of about 0.4 arcseconds.  The goal is to avoid over resolving Ceres, but also to schedule the observations when Ceres is well positioned with respect to the Sun.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Simple scaling from previous detections of water vapor on Ceres yield an estimated line absorption depth of ~0.2%.  The line width wil be about 1 km/s, similar to what was previously observed, and matching expectations based on Ceres' escape velocity and on the rms velocity for water molecules at ~200K, the daytime temperatures for Ceres.  During Cycle 3 Ceres will be about 3 AU from the sun (near aphelion) and about 3.5 AU away from Earth, leading to an estimated Band 7 flux density of 1.3 Jy.  Thus, the previous observations suggest that the line depth may be ~2.5mJy for a 1.3 Jy continuum target.  However, this prediction is extremely uncertain owing to the limited previous detections and the possibility that the emission is *highly* variable.

Therefore, I am requesting observations that will fit in a single block of time to either set an upper limit of 51 mJy rms in the line (17 mJy rms sensitivity for a 1 km/sec spectral resolution).

Ceres is bright enough to phase cal, so in addition to requesting a high resolution spectral window centered on the expected line, I also have requested TDM spectral windows, one also centered on the spectral line, and the other two centered in a clear part of the spectrum for improved calibration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
