    <prp:abstract>This project will search for absorption from water vapor against the bright thermal emission from Ceres at 325.153 GHz.  These are risky observations:  a null detection would only place an upper limit on water vapor near Ceres above the amount already detected by the Herschel spacecraft.  However, a positive result would confirm that water vapor production on Ceres is highly variable and would also strongly imply that Ceres water vapor is cryovolcanic rather than comet-like in origin, since Ceres will be near its maximum solar distance during Cycle 3 when comet-like emission would be at a minimum.

Large and highly variable amounts of water vapor on Ceres would increase the possibility that Ceres could harbor liquid water within its predicted icy mantle.  Such a result would increase interest in further observations and exploration of Ceres, since reservoirs of liquid water are thought to be one of the essential requirements for the evolution of life.  </prp:abstract>
